\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li48\sb720\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-1\fs21 It is quite customary for a piece of fiction to contain at least \expndtw3 the threat of disaster. It is the threat, the menace, the ap\-\expndtw0 prehension of something one desperately does not want to \expndtw4 take place that creates the suspense, and that rouses the \expndtw1 interest of the reader.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi250\li34\ri10\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-2\fs21 To be sure, the disaster may be a very slight and personal \expndtw-1 one-the youngster who may fail the test, or lose the game, or be turned down for a date-but it is there. To be equally \expndtw0 sure, the story may be a lighthearted one with a happy end\-\expndtw3 ing, but the disaster, however slight, must be there in the \expndtw0 mid-course for the ending to shine happily against.\cf0\lang2057\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi235\li34\ri24\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw2\fs21 This is not to say that a story cannot be written without \expndtw1 a disaster, but what a dull story it would be and how little worth the reading.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li269\sl-197\slmult0\tx3749\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-5\fs21 And, as in so many other respects, science \expndtw-3 fiction  manages\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li29\ri29\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-4\fs21 to outshine other types of fiction. Where but in science fiction \expndtw-1 can \i real \i0 disasters be found?\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi240\li24\ri29\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw2\fs21 Take the most elaborate of realistic suspense and what \expndtw-6 can you have? The loss of a war? The enslavement of a nation?\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-4\fs21 In science fiction, the destruction of civilization is the least \expndtw1 one might expect as the threat of disaster, or its actual ac\-\expndtw0 complishment, is represented to the reader.\cf0\lang2057\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi250\li14\ri24\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\fs21 In this collection of twenty stories, we have four stories \expndtw-5 dealing with each of five different levels of disaster, organized \expndtw-1 according to a scheme I devised in my nonfiction discussion \expndtw-5 entitled A \i Choice of Catastrophes \i0 (Simon and Schuster, 1979; \expndtw-2 Fawcett Columbine, 1981),\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi250\ri38\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-1\fs21 The movement is from the most all-encompassing catas\-\expndtw1 trophes toward progressively narrower ones. If this sounds \expndtw0 to you like a journey into anticlimax, you are wrong, for as \expndtw-1 the catastrophes become narrower, they also become more \expndtw-2 probable. In short, in this book you may be steadily decreas\-\expndtw0 ing the scope but you are as steadily increasing the danger.\cf0\lang2057\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li250\sl-197\slmult0\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-2\fs21 Why bother? Why scare yourself?\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi250\li5\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-2\fs21 For one thing, these are memorable stories you will enjoy \expndtw-1 and won't easily forget. For another, humanity \i does \i0 face ca\-tastrophes of various levels of scope and various gradations \expndtw-4 of likelihood, and if there is any chance at all of evading them \expndtw-2 or blunting them, that chance will be heightened if we know \expndtw0 what the dangers may be and consider in advance how to \expndtw1 prevent or ameliorate them.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
