\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi245\ri24\sl-192\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\fs21 Neither of us made much fuss. It was unexpected, but it \expndtw-1 did seem so natural for him to be there, after all, much more \expndtw0 natural than for him not be there, and he was too tired to be \expndtw1 very emotional. We lay there together in the dark, and he \expndtw-2 explained that they had released him from the Rehabilitation \expndtw1 Camp early because he had injured his back in an accident \expndtw-2 in the gravel quarry, and they were afraid it might get worse.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li2357\sl-192\slmult0\qj\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\sl-187\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-1\fs21 If he died there it wouldn't be good publicity abroad, since \expndtw-4 there have been some nasty rumors about deaths from illness in\expndtw0  the Rehabilitation Camps and the Federal Medical As\-\expndtw-3 sociation Hospitals, and there are scientists abroad who have h\expndtw-5 eard of Simon, since somebody published his proof of Gold-\expndtw-1 bach's Hypothesis in Peking, So they let him out early, with \expndtw-4 eight dollars in his pocket, which is what he had in his pocket \expndtw-1 when they arrested him, which made it, of course, fair. He had walked and hitched home from Coeur D'Alene, Idaho, \expndtw-2 with a couple of days in jail in Walla Walla for being caught \expndtw-1 hitchhiking. He almost fell asleep telling me this, and when he had told me, he did fall asleep. He needed a change of \expndtw2 clothes and a bath but I didn't want to wake him. Besides, \expndtw-2 I was tired, too. We lay side by side and his head was on my arm. I don't suppose that I have ever been so happy. No; was it happiness? Something wider and darker, more like knowl\-\expndtw-1 edge, more like the night: joy.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li485\ri29\sb360\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-4\i\fs21 It was dark for so long, so very long. We were all blind. \expndtw-2 And there was the cold, a vast, unmoving, heavy cold. \expndtw-4 We could not move at all. We did not move. We did not \expndtw-6 speak. Our mouths were closed, pressed shut by the cold and by the weight. Our eyes were pressed shut. Our limbs were held still. Our minds were held still. For how long? \expndtw1 There was no length of time; how long is death? And \expndtw-4 is one dead only after living, or before life as well? Cer\-\expndtw-3 tainly we thought, if we thought anything, that we were \expndtw-4 dead; but if we had ever been alive, we had forgotten it.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi254\li475\ri43\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-3\i\fs21 There was a change. It must have been the pressure \expndtw-2 that changed first, although we did not know it. The \expndtw-6 eyelids are sensitive to touch. They must have been weary \expndtw-1 of being shut. When the pressure upon them weakened \expndtw-6 a little, they opened. But there was no way for us \i0 to \i know \expndtw-4 that. It was too cold for us to feel anything. There was \expndtw-3 nothing to be seen. There was black.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi302\li398\ri58\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-3\i\fs21 But then-"'then," for the event created time, created \expndtw-4  before and after, near and far, now and then\i0 -\i "then" \expndtw-2 there was the light. One light. One small, strange light \expndtw-1 that passed slowly, at what distance we could not tell. \expndtw-2 A small, greenish white, slightly blurred point of ra\-\expndtw-3 diance, passing.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li442\ri77\sb5\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-3\i\fs21 Our eyes were certainly open, "then," for we saw it. We saw the moment. The moment in a point of light. Whether in darkness or in the field of all light, the mo-\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li53\ri10\sl-202\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw3\i ment is small, and moves, but not quickly. And "then" \expndtw-1 it is gone.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi235\li38\sl-202\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw1\i It did not occur to us that there might be another \expndtw-3 moment. There was no reason to assume that there might \expndtw1 be more than one. One was marvel enough: that in all \expndtw-2 the field of the dark, in the cold, heavy, dense, moveless, \expndtw-1 timeless, placeless, boundless black, there should have occurred, once, a small slightly blurred, moving light! \expndtw0 Time need be created only once, we thought.\cf0\lang2057\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi240\li29\ri14\sl-202\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw1\i But we were mistaken. The difference between one and more than one is all the difference in the world. Indeed, that difference is the world.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li288\sl-202\slmult0\cf1\lang1033\expndtw2\i The light returned.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li283\sl-202\slmult0\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-2\i The same light, or another one? There was no telling.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi226\li38\ri10\sl-202\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw3\i But, "this time," we wondered about the light: Was \expndtw0 it small and near to us, or large and far away? Again \expndtw-1 there was no telling; but there was something about the \expndtw0 way it moved, a trace of hesitation, a tentative quality, that did not seem proper to anything large and remote. \expndtw-2 The stars, for instance. We began to remember the stars.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li283\sl-202\slmult0\cf1\lang1033\expndtw1\i The stars had never hesitated.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi230\li24\ri14\sl-202\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\i Perhaps the noble certainty of their gait had been a \expndtw-2 mere effect of distance. Perhaps in fact they had hurtled \expndtw0 wildly, enormous furnace-fragments of a primal bomb \expndtw1 thrown through the cosmic dark; but time and distance \expndtw0 soften all agony. If the universe, as seems likely, began \expndtw-2 with an act of destruction, the "Stars we had used to see \expndtw1 told no tales of it. They had been implacably serene.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi264\li5\ri24\sb5\sl-202\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-1\i The planets, however... We began to remember the \expndtw0 planets. They had suffered certain changes both of ap\-\expndtw-3 pearance and of course. At certain times of the year Mars \expndtw-2 would reverse its direction and go backward through the \expndtw1 stars. Venus had been brighter and less bright as she \expndtw-1 went through her phases of crescent, full, and wane. \expndtw0 Mercury had shuddered like a skidding drop of rain on \expndtw-2 the sky flushed with daybreak. The light we now watched \expndtw3 had that erratic, trembling quality. We saw it, unmis\-\expndtw-2 takably, change direction and go backward. It then grew smaller and fainter; blinked\i0 -\i an eclipse?\i0 -\i and slowly disappeared.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
