\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi269\li10\ri10\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw1\fs21 I make Simon laugh, too, though I don't intend to. We \expndtw0 talked until it was past time for me to go to work. My shift since the Full Employment Act last year is ten to two. I am \expndtw-1 an inspector in a recycled paper bag factory. I have never \expndtw0 rejected a bag yet; the electronic inspector catches all the \expndtw-2 defective ones first. It is a rather depressing job. But it's only \expndtw2 four hours a day, and it takes more time than that to go \expndtw-1 through all the lines and physical and mental examinations, \expndtw-4 and fill out all the forms, and talk to all the welfare counselors and inspectors every week in order to qualify as Unemployed, \expndtw-3 and then line up every day for the ration stamps and the dole. \expndtw0 Simon thought I ought to go to work as usual. I tried to, but \expndtw1 I couldn't. He had felt very hot to the touch when I kissed \expndtw-2 him goed-bye. I went instead and got a black-market doctor. \expndtw0 A girl at the factory had recommended her, for an abortion, \expndtw1 if I ever wanted one without going through the regulation \expndtw0 two years of sex-depressant drugs the fed-meds make you take when they give you an abortion. She was a jeweler's \expndtw-1 assistant in a shop on Alder Street, and the girl said she was \expndtw-3 convenient because if you didn't have enough cash you could \expndtw-4 leave something in pawn at the jeweler's as payment. Nobody \expndtw-2 ever does have enough cash, and of course credit cards aren't \expndtw1 worth much on the black market.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi245\ri34\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-2\fs21 The doctor was willing to come at once, so we rode home \expndtw0 on the bus together. She gathered very soon that Simon and \expndtw1 I were married, and it was funny to see her look at us and \expndtw-3 smile like a cat. Some people love illegality for its own sake. \expndtw-2 Men, more often than women. It's men who make laws, and \expndtw0 enforce them, and break them, and think the whole perfor\-\expndtw1 mance is wonderful. Most women would rather just ignore\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\fs20\par
