\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li24\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw4 them. You could see that this woman, like a man, actually \expndtw5 enjoyed breaking them. That may have been what put her \expndtw2 into an illegal business in the first place, a preference for the \expndtw6 shady side. But there was more to it than that. No doubt \expndtw2 she'd wanted to be a doctor, too; and the Federal Medical Association doesn't admit women into the medical schools. \expndtw3 She probably got her training as some other doctor's private \expndtw2 pupil, under the counter. Very much as Simon learned math\-\expndtw1 ematics, since the universities don't teach much but Business \expndtw2 Administration and Advertising and Media Skills any more. \expndtw3 However she learned it, she seemed to know her stuff. She \expndtw1 fixed up a kind of homemade traction device for Simon very \expndtw3 handily and informed him that if he did much more walking \expndtw2 for two months he'd be crippled the rest of his life, but if he \expndtw3 behaved himself he'd just be more or less lame. It isn't the kind of thing you'd expect to be grateful for being told, but we both were. Leaving, she gave me a bottle of about two \expndtw4 hundred plain white pills, unlabeled. "Aspirin," she said. \expndtw2 "He'll be in a good deal of pain off and on for weeks."\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\par
