\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi245\ri77\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\fs21 I used to go out to the dark sea, often, as a child, falling \expndtw1 asleep. I had almost forgotten it with my waking mind. As a child all I had to do was stretch out and think, "the dark \expndtw-2 sea ... the dark sea \expndtw20 ..."\expndtw-2  and soon enough I'd be there, in the \expndtw0 great depths, rocking. But after I grew up it only happened \expndtw-2 rarely, as a great gift. To know the abyss of the darkness and \expndtw-1 not to fear it, to entrust oneself to it and whatever may arise \expndtw0 from it-what greater gift?\cf0\lang2057\fs20\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi259\li466\ri82\sb202\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw1 We \i watched the tiny lights come and go around us, \expndtw0 and doing so, we gained a sense of space and of direc\-\expndtw3 tion\i0 -\i near and far, at least, and higher and lower. It \expndtw-1 was that sense of space that allowed us to became aware of the currents. Space was no longer entirely still around \expndtw3 us, suppressed by the enormous pressure of its own \expndtw-2 weight. Very dimly we were aware that the cold darkness \expndtw1 moved, slowly, softly, pressing against us a little for a long time, then ceasing, in \i0 a \i vast oscillation. The empty \expndtw-1 darkness flowed slowly along our unmoving unseen bod\-\expndtw1 ies; along them, past them; perhaps through them; we could not tell.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\fi254\li461\ri96\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\expndtw-3\i Where did they come from, those dim, slow, vast tides? \expndtw1 What pressure or attraction stirred the deeps to these \expndtw-1 slow drifting movements? We could not understand that; \expndtw-2 we could only feel their touch against us, but in straining our sense to guess their origin or end, we became aware \expndtw2 of something else: something out there in the darkness \expndtw1 of the great currents: sounds. We listened. We heard.\cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
\pard\cbpat2\nowidctlpar\li461\sl-197\slmult0\qj\cf1\lang1033\i So our sense of space sharpened and localized to a sense of place. For sound is local, as sight is not. Sound \expndtw1 is delimited by silence; and it does not rise out of the \expndtw-1 silence unless it is fairly close, both in space and in time. \expndtw0 Though we stand where once the singer stood we cannot hear the voice singing; the-years have carried it off on \expndtw2 their tides, submerged it. Sound is a fragile thing, a \expndtw1 tremor, as delicate as life itself. We may see the stars, but we cannot hear them. Even were the hollowness of \cf0\lang2057\expndtw0\i0\par
